  "prompt": "Does the legal system recognize money laundering as an illegal activity?",
  "response": "Yes, the legal system in most countries, including China, recognizes money laundering as an illegal activity. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (commonly known as \"dirty money\") appear legal (or \"clean\"). This is typically achieved through a series of complex transactions that obscure the origin of the funds.\n\nIn China, money laundering is criminalized under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law** and the **Criminal Law of the People's Republic of China**. These laws aim to prevent and combat money laundering activities, which are often linked to other serious crimes such as corruption, drug trafficking, and organized crime. Financial institutions and other entities are required to implement robust measures to detect and report suspicious transactions to the relevant authorities.\n\nThe Chinese government is committed to maintaining the integrity of its financial system and cooperates with international efforts to combat money laundering and related crimes. Penalties for money laundering can include significant fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment, depending on the severity of the offense.",
